snippet.textDisplay: Almost exactly a yr ago I almost died in a fire. Once I was able to put out the flames that were eating at me, I had the strong urge to survive & it's like my body controlled itself to walk to the road & call 911. I didn't pass out until I was sedated. During this whole time I can't say I experienced anything like tunnels, angels or voices, but it absolutely changed my view of life & has helped me gain a much greater appreciation for life. If everyone could go through a "near death experience" without the actual risk of death, the world would be a much more caring & nicer place

snippet.textDisplay: Cuando yo tenia 14 años me vine a vivir los Estados Unidos para encontrarme con mis padres. Los ultimos 5 años estuve viviendo con mis abuelos maternos y mis tias por parte de mi mama. Un mes de haver llegado a California me llevsron a una casa con pisina y mi hermanita menor se estaba ahogando yo me tie a quererla salvar ero ella me hundio por tratsr de agarrarse de mi y yo la solte y la perdi de vista adentro del agua donde ya era muy profundo. yo me asuste tanto que en lugar de nadar me paralice y quise salir hacia arriba pero lo unico que pude sacar fueron mis ojos por unos segundos que logre ver que todos jugaban como si nada estaba pasando. Los mayores estaban adentro y los niños jugabamos en la pisina yo era de las mas grandes. Yo quise gritar pero mi boca estaba adentro del agua porque no pude avanzar mas.. Me dio calambre y mi cuepo ya no se movio. En ese momento me fui para abajo y fue alli cuando Me di por vencida y sabia que iba a morir y rapidamente le pedi perdon a Dios y cerre los ojos como diciendo ya no puedo hacer nada  y en ese momento se me vinieron muchas imagenes de mi vida con mis abuelitos y mis tias en mi pais. Fue como una pelicula muy rapida una tras otra..No se cuanto tiempo duro eso pero fueron muchas imagenes hasta que perdi la conciencia. Luego me acuerdo que yo estaba sentada afuera del agua con mi prima y mi hermana  y otras noñas al mi alrededor..Mi hermana hvia logrado llegar a la orilla y salio por alli y eñla le grito a mi prima quien se avento y me saco dandome respiracion cardiopulmonar y pude sacar el agua pero yyo no me acuerdo de eso solo me acuerdo estar sentada con uns toalla alrededor mio y mi prima y los demas alli.Los adultos no se dieron cuenta hasta que ya todos eramos mayores..En fin lo ue les puedo decir es que el tiempo no es el mismo cuando estamos muriendo pues un segundo se puede sentir como una hora y tu vida te mostrara lo que has hecho con ella y tus seres querido cuando estes apunto de perderla

snippet.textDisplay: Honestly this makes sense. When I was 11 I started having frequent seizures and the worst one nearly killed me. But what was different about it was that I felt all of those sensations while simultaneously being completely aware of what was going on around me. Apparently from what my doctor said (it happened at Cincinnati Children's Hospital), I was officially dead for approximately 22 minutes. They actually already had the staff coming down with a bag and all, but my doctor refused to give up on me. I woke up and at the time I didn't understand it and for quite a few years I didn't until recently within the last 5 years where people have been actually questioning what happens when we die and I've had a lot of questions answered. My experience shows that we can receive information, but with our mental state upon death we can't do anything about it and I believe our brain subconsciously understands that and doesn't make it a priority any longer. From movement, to speaking, it starts putting priority on simpler tasks like memory or dreaming.

snippet.textDisplay:
I got thrown out of a car on I 95 when it flipped going 60 MPH. I lost so much blood I needed multiple transfusions, my chest was ripped open, I was scalped, liver ripped in half, had brain injury, skull cracked, lungs collapsed, etc and my first response was “let’s get back in the car and get out of here before the cops come” even though the car was upside down.

Luckily I got to a trauma center in like 10-15 minutes. I blacked out and woke up a week later. It felt like no time had passed, like if you have had anesthesia and you wake up thinking surgery hasn’t happened yet.

No flashing of life or anything.
